06139nam a22009135i 9780812202144DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122021447 a10.9783/97808122021442doi  a(DE-B1597)449074  a(OCoLC)979577918  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE78.S65bH35 2009eb 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a973.22221 aHall, Jr., Joseph M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZamumo's Gifts :bIndian-European Exchange in the Colonial Southeast /cJoseph M. Hall, Jr. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Spirit of a Feather: The Politics of Mississippian Exchange -- t2. Floods and Feathers: From the Mississippian to the Floridian -- t3. Seeking the Atlantic: The Growth of Trade -- t4. Following the White Path: Migration and the Muskogees’ Quest for Security -- t5. Creating White Hearts: Anxious Alliances amid the Slave Trade -- t6. The Yamasee War: Trade Reformed, a Region Reoriented -- t7. Cries of ‘‘Euchee!’’: Imperial Trade in a Creek Southeast -- tConclusion: Gifts and Trade, Towns and Empires -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Native Place Names -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1540, Zamumo, the chief of the Altamahas in central Georgia, exchanged gifts with the Spanish conquistador Hernando de Soto. With these gifts began two centuries of exchanges that bound American Indians and the Spanish, English, and French who colonized the region. Whether they gave gifts for diplomacy or traded commodities for profit, Natives and newcomers alike used the exchange of goods such as cloth, deerskin, muskets, and sometimes people as a way of securing their influence. Gifts and trade enabled early colonies to survive and later colonies to prosper. Conversely, they upset the social balance of chiefdoms like Zamumo's and promoted the rise of new and powerful Indian confederacies like the Creeks and the Choctaws.Drawing on archaeological studies, colonial documents from three empires, and Native oral histories, Joseph M. Hall, Jr., offers fresh insights into broad segments of southeastern colonial history, including the success of Florida's Franciscan missionaries before 1640 and the impact of the Indian slave trade on French Louisiana after 1699. He also shows how gifts and trade shaped the Yamasee War, which pitted a number of southeastern tribes against English South Carolina in 1715-17. The exchanges at the heart of Zamumo's Gifts highlight how the history of Europeans and Native Americans cannot be understood without each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEuropeansvCommercevSouthern StatesxHistoryx17th century. 0aEuropeansvCommercevSouthern StatesxHistoryx18th century. 0aEuropeansxCommercezSouthern StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aEuropeansxCommercezSouthern StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aHISTORYzUnited StatesvColonial Period (1600-1775). 0aIndians of North AmericavColonial period. 0aIndians of North AmericavCommercevSouthern StatesxHistoryx17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericavCommercevSouthern StatesxHistoryx18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericavFirst contact with EuropeansvSouthern States. 0aIndians of North AmericavSouthern StatesxHistoryvColonial period, ca. 1600-1775. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCommercezSouthern StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCommercezSouthern StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst cont